## Case Study: CAN Not Working Due to RS Pin Misconfiguration

### Problem
CAN communication was not getting established between nodes.
- No frames observed on bus
- CAN working in loopback mode but not able to transmit in Normal Mode
- No ACK was happening in the BUS
- Software configuration appeared correct
---

### My Initial Assumptions
- Suspected firmware issue (bit timing, filters)
- Verified CAN initialization multiple times
- Checked baud rate → correct
- Tried Different baud rate with different sampling rate

---

### Investigation

After prolonged debugging on software side, hardware was rechecked.

Observation:
- RS(Slope Control) pin of CAN transceiver was connected through a resistor nor even hard GND connected.
- This caused incorrect mode configuration

---

### Root Cause

The RS (slope control) pin controls:
- Operating mode (high-speed vs standby)
- Signal edge rate (affects communication reliability)

Due to improper connection:
- Transceiver was not operating in proper high-speed mode
- CAN bus signaling was not correctly driven

---

### Fix
- RS pin was properly grounded (or configured as per datasheet)
- Removed incorrect resistor configuration (# Very Important)

Result:
- CAN communication established immediately

---

### Key Learning

- CAN controller debugging is misleading — many failures are hardware-related
- Transceiver pins (like RS) are critical and often overlooked
- Always verify transceiver configuration before deep software debugging

---

### Practical Insight

If:
- No communication at all
- No dominant/recessive activity visible

Then check:
- Transceiver mode pins (RS, STB, EN)
- Not just MCU configuration


# Bonus Tip:
Always verify the idle voltage of CAN_H and CAN_L using a multimeter or oscilloscope.
In a healthy bus, both lines stay at their recessive levels when no transmission occurs.
Incorrect idle levels indicate a physical layer issue—communication will fail regardless of firmware correctness.
